<paragraph blockId="4.[227,341,1767,1793]" box="[227,341,1767,1793]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,341,1767,1793]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,341,1767,1793]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[227,1437,1815,2063]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">
Due to differing opinions on the significance of the general shape of the conch, there is disagreement on the species spectrum of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[669,786,1853,1878]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[669,786,1853,1878]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Turner J. S." box="[800,965,1852,1879]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" pagination="689 - 692" refId="ref18623" refString="Turner J. S. 1953. The nautiloids named in Martin's &quot; Petrificata Derbiensia, 1809 &quot;. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 6: 689 - 692. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222935308654470" type="journal article" year="1953">Turner (1953)</bibRefCitation>
revised the species originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Martin W." box="[265,424,1889,1915]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" refId="ref18264" refString="Martin W. 1793. Figures and Descriptions of Petrifications Collected in Derbyshire, Wigan." type="book" year="1793">Martin (1793</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Martin W." box="[438,498,1889,1915]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" refId="ref18292" refString="Martin W. 1809. Petrificata Derbiensia: or, Figures and Descriptions of Petrifactions Collected in Derbyshire. Vol. 1. Lyon, Wigan. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119699" type="book" year="1809">1809</bibRefCitation>
) as “Conchyliolithus N. Ammonites (
<emphasis box="[947,1017,1889,1915]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">Luidii</emphasis>
)”, and subsequently, he introduced the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="1954" box="[350,519,1926,1951]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Pararineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[350,519,1926,1951]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">Pararineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Turner J. S." box="[864,1013,1925,1952]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" pagination="298 - 325" refId="ref18664" refString="Turner J. S. 1954. On the Carboniferous nautiloids: some Middle Visean species from the Isle of Man. Liverpool and Manchester Geological Journal 1: 298 - 325. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / gj. 3350010307" type="journal article" year="1954">Turner 1954</bibRefCitation>
). This species differs from the 
<typeStatus box="[1386,1437,1926,1952]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[351,468,1963,1988]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[351,468,1963,1988]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only by the more densely coiled conch and the supposed “straightening out in late maturity”. The first of these two characters might be gradual and not useful for a separation of genera and the second cannot really be demonstrated in the 
<typeStatus box="[792,898,2036,2062]" pageId="4" pageNumber="71">holotype</typeStatus>
, which has a conch diameter of only 
<quantity box="[1334,1420,2036,2063]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="71" unit="mm" value="28.0">28 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[227,1436,303,400]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">
<bibRefCitation author="Kummel B." box="[227,414,303,329]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" pagination="466" refId="ref18219" refString="Kummel B. 1964. Nautiloidea-Nautilida. In: Moore R. C. (ed.) Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology: K 383 - K 466. The Geological Society of America and The University of Kansas Press, Lawrence, KS." type="book chapter" year="1964">Kummel (1964)</bibRefCitation>
accepted both genera without providing clear distinguishing characters, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Shimansky V. N." pageId="5" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 244" refId="ref18477" refString="Shimansky V. N. 1967. Kamennougol'nye Nautilida. Trudy Paleontologicheskogo Instituta Akademiya Nauk SSSR 115: 1 - 244." type="journal article" year="1967">Shimansky (1967)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Dzik J." box="[364,507,338,364]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 219" refId="ref17507" refString="Dzik J. 1984. Phylogeny of the Nautiloidea. Palaeontologia Polonica 45: 1 - 219." type="journal article" year="1984">Dzik (1984)</bibRefCitation>
regarded 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="1954" box="[626,795,339,364]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Pararineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[626,795,339,364]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Pararineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[1004,1121,339,364]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1004,1121,339,364]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the following, we treat 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Turner" authorityYear="1954" box="[227,396,375,400]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Pararineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[227,396,375,400]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Pararineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[680,797,375,400]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[680,797,375,400]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
until a clear separation can be demonstrated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[226,1436,440,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[227,344,441,466]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[227,344,441,466]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted here to those species that have a whorl profile with a rounded outline. This means that the species 
<taxonomicName authority="Meekianus Winchell, 1862" authorityName="Meekianus Winchell" authorityYear="1862" box="[429,1067,475,501]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Nautilidae" genus="Nautilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Trematodiscus">
<emphasis box="[429,528,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Nautilus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[551,721,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Trematodiscus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[743,870,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Meekianus</emphasis>
Winchell, 1862
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Winchell, 1862" authorityName="Winchell" authorityYear="1862" class="Cephalopoda" family="Nautilidae" genus="Nautilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="strigatus" subGenus="Trematodiscus">
<emphasis box="[1135,1234,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Nautilus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1256,1426,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Trematodiscus</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[227,330,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">strigatus</emphasis>
Winchell, 1862
</taxonomicName>
, both with longitudinal grooves on the venter, placed in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[1173,1290,512,537]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1173,1290,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Miller A. K. &amp; Garner H. F." pageId="5" pageNumber="72" pagination="111 - 151" refId="ref18389" refString="Miller A. K. &amp; Garner H. F. 1953. Lower Mississippian cephalopods of Michigan. Part II. Coiled nautiloids. Contributions of the Museum of Paleontology, University of Michigan 11: 111 - 151." type="journal article" year="1953">Miller &amp; Garner (1953)</bibRefCitation>
, are excluded from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[629,746,547,572]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[629,746,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and listed in the new genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[1080,1268,546,572]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Stroborineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1080,1268,546,572]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Stroborineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1275,1382,547,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[225,1439,612,781]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[227,344,613,638]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[227,344,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the ancestral Early Carboniferous genera in the evolution of the nautilid family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1884" box="[229,432,648,674]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Trigonoceratidae</taxonomicName>
. This is supported not only by the early stratigraphic occurrence in strata of the early late Tournaisian, but also by the morphology with a rather simple overall whorl profile without the longitudinal grooves and ridges often present in many derived forms, which there lead to a more complex geometry.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
